[[File:Ardha-Matsyendrasana Yoga-Asana Nina-Mel.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Ardha Matsyendrasana I, a commonly practised half form of the pose]]

{{Contains Indic text}}
'''Matsyendrasana''' ({{lang-sa|मत्स्येन्द्रासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''Matsyendrāsana''), '''Lord of the Fishes Pose''', is an [[asana]] in [[hatha yoga]]. The full form is the difficult '''Paripurna Matsyendrasana''' ({{lang-sa|परिपूर्णमत्स्येन्द्रासन}}), from paripurna, perfected, [[Matsyendra]], one of the founders of hatha yoga, and asana, posture or seat. A common and easier variant is '''Ardha Matsyendrasana''' ({{lang-sa|अर्धमत्स्येन्द्रासन}}, from ardha, half.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/485 | title=Half Lord of the Fishes Pose | accessdate=9 April 2011 | publisher=Yoga Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yogapoint.com/asana/matsyendrasana.html | title=Yoga poses, Ardha Matsyendrasana, Half Spinal Twist: | accessdate=9 April 2011}}</ref> The asana usually appears as a [[sitting|seated]] spinal twist with many variations, and in its half form is one of the twelve basic asanas in many systems of hatha yoga.<ref name=Advaita>{{cite web |title=The Half Spinal Twist - Ardha-Matsyendrasana |url=http://yoga108.org/pages/show/107-ardha-matsyendrasana-the-half-spinal-twist-yoga-posture |work=Hatha Yoga |publisher=Advaita Yoga Ashrama |accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref>

== Etymology ==

The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''ardha'' meaning "half", Matsyendra, one of the founders of [[hatha yoga]],{{sfn|Iyengar|1979|p=273}}<ref name="MaehleGauci2009">{{cite book | last1=Maehle | first1=Gregor
| last2=Gauci | first2=Monica | title=Ashtanga Yoga - The Intermediate Series: Mythology, Anatomy, and Practice | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OhYeGdNK0UoC&pg=PA43 | date=November 2009 | publisher=New World Library | isbn=978-1-57731-669-5 | page=43}}</ref> (whose name in turn means "lord of the fishes") and ''asana'' (आसन ) meaning "posture" or "seat".<ref name="Long2011">{{cite book | last=Long | first=Ray | title=Yoga Mat Companion 3: Anatomy for Backbends and Twists | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGTIdmn6RgsC&pg=PA162 | accessdate=9 April 2011
| date=22 January 2011 | publisher=Greenleaf Book (Distributor) | isbn=978-1-60743-944-8 | page=162}}</ref>

== Description ==

One foot is placed flat on the floor outside the opposite leg and torso twists toward the top leg.  The bottom leg may be bent with the foot outside the opposite hip or extended with toes vertically.  The arms help leverage the torso into the twist and may be bound (Baddha Ardha Matsyendrasana) in a number of configurations by clutching either feet or opposite hands.

==Variations==

===Ardha Matsyendrasana I===

In this pose, sit with one leg bent on the ground, the foot tucked in close to the body, and cross the other leg over across the body, the knee raised and bent, and the foot on the ground by the outside of the other leg. Twist the body and grasp the raised knee; or, bring the arm over to press against the raised knee; or clasp the hands behind the back.<ref name="Iyengar Light on Yoga">{{cite book |last=Iyengar |first=B. K. S. |title=Light on Yoga |year=1979 |publisher=Schocken Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8052-0610-4 |edition=Revised |pages=259–262, 270-273}}</ref>

<!--===Ardha Matsyendrasana II===
<ref name="Iyengar Light on Yoga" />
-->
===Ardha Matsyendrasana III===
From Ardha Matsyendrasana I, the bottom leg moves into Padmasana (Lotus Position) and arms bind by grabbing either foot.<ref name="Iyengar Light on Yoga" />

== Benefits ==

Ardha Matsyendrāsana allows the spine to be twisted all the way from the base of the spine to the very top.  This asana is said to tone the spinal nerves and ligaments, and improves digestion and also improve liver and pancreas health<ref name="Yogeswar1980">{{cite book | author=Yogeswar | title=Textbook of yoga | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eRUaAAAAMAAJ | year=1980 | publisher=Yoga Centre| page=161}}</ref> The ''[[Hatha Yoga Pradipika]]'' states<!--in verse 27--> that it increases appetite, destroys diseases, and rouses [[kundalini]] in the body.{{sfn|Iyengar|1979|p=273}}

