{{IndicText}}
'''Salabhasana''', '''Shalabhasana''' ({{lang-sa|शलभासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''Śalabhāsana''), '''Locust Pose''',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/789 | title = Yoga Journal - Locust Pose | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> or '''Grasshopper Pose'''<ref name="YesudianHaich1953">{{cite book |last1=Yesudian |first1=Selvarajan |last2=Haich |first2=Elisabeth |title=Yoga and health |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jsnXAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=January 1953 |publisher=Harper |page=139}}</ref> is a back-bending yoga [[asana]]<ref> Salabhasana http://yoganga.com/articles/salabhasana/</ref>.
==Etymology==
The name comes from the Sanskrit words "shalabh" which means "grasshopper".
==Description==
It is a back bend, or spine stretch, utilizing the strength of the upper and middle back to lift the weight of the legs as high as possible from a starting position while face down on the floor. It improves flexibility and coordination and increases strength and stamina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc-of-yoga.com/yogapractice/thelocust.asp|title=Yoga Exercise - Locust Pose (Salabhasana)|publisher=www.abc-of-yoga.com|accessdate=2008-11-29|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210032301/http://www.abc-of-yoga.com/yogapractice/thelocust.asp|archivedate=10 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Structural Yoga Therapy: Adapting to the Individual|first= Mukunda|last= Stiles|publisher=Red Wheel|year= 2000|isbn=1-57863-177-7}}</ref> it helps to exercise the spine.
==Cautions== Beginners may find that their shoulder and elbow flexibility is not sufficient to allow them to get the hands palm down right underneath the body.
==Variations== Variations of this asana are: * Ardha Salabhasana (Half Locust Pose)<ref name="Pratap1997">{{cite book |last=Pratap |first=Vijayendra |title=Beginning Yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Z0zcWPkxNkC&pg=PA26 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=15 September 1997 |publisher=Tuttle Publishing |isbn=978-0-8048-2104-9 |page=26}}</ref><ref name="Mohanty">{{cite book |author=Mohanty |title=Managing Common Musculoskeletal Conditions by Physiotherapy & Yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LTmvNMD1pYEC&pg=PA15 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |publisher=Jaypee Brothers Publishers |isbn=978-81-8448-357-4 |page=15}}</ref> * Poorna Salabhasana (Full Locust Pose)<ref name="Inc.1996">{{cite book |author=Active Interest Media, Inc. |title=Yoga Journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fekDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=August 1996 |publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc. |page=14 |issn=0191-0965}}</ref>
In the [[Bikram Yoga|Bikram style of yoga]], the asana referred to as Salabhasana has three stages which follow one after the other.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} The asana of the same name in the [[Astanga Yoga|Astanga style of yoga]] corresponds to stage three of the Bikram style asana.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}
==Preparatory asanas== In several styles of yoga, including [[Bikram Yoga]] and [[Astanga Yoga]], Salabhasana is commonly performed after [[Bhujangasana]], a related asana working on a different part of the spine.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
