{{Infobox book | name = Sex, Sin, and Zen: A Buddhist Exploration of Sex from Celibacy to Polyamory and Everything in Between | image = Sex, Sin, and Zen.jpg | caption = | author = [[Brad Warner]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = [[Harvey Pekar]] | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Sōtō]] [[Zen|Zen Buddhism]] | publisher = [[New World Library]] | release_date = August 21, 2010 | media_type = Print | pages = 304 | isbn = 978-1-57731-910-8 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = [[Zen Wrapped in Karma Dipped in Chocolate]] | followed_by = [[Death to All Monsters!]] }}
'''''Sex, Sin, and Zen: A Buddhist Exploration of Sex from Celibacy to Polyamory and Everything in Between''''' is a book written by [[Zen]] [[priest]] and [[punk rock]] [[bassist]] [[Brad Warner]]. The book is an exploration of sex from a modern Zen Buddhist perspective.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=John L. |title=''Sex, Sin, and Zen'': 25 Years Hardcore: as Punk Bassist, Sexual Seeker, and Zen Student |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/129943-sex-sin-and-zen-by-brad-warner |work=Pop Matters |accessdate=20 June 2011}}</ref> It alternates between practical chapters and more arcane, conceptual ones.
The book also features an interview with [[porn star]] [[Nina Hartley]] who was raised in [[Berkeley, California]] by two Zen Buddhists.
==Reception== The book received mostly positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tricycle.com/p/2295 |title=Sex, Sin, and Zen |accessdate=May 17, 2012 |publisher=[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review]] }}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' said of the book, "The subject is as fundamental as the human sex drive, which does not go away as one spends time on the cushion...Kudos to Warner for tackling the subject."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-57731-910-8 |title=Religion review: Sex, Sin, and Zen |accessdate=May 17, 2012 |publisher=[[Publishers Weekly]] }}</ref>
The book has been seen as being alternatively too positive towards polyamory and too critical of it.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rotondi |first=James |title=Sex, Sin & Zen: Brad Warner and the Lust for Enlightenment|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/james-rotondi/brad-warner-zen-_b_873882.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=20 June 2011}}</ref>
