{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[French philosophy]] | era = [[18th-century philosophy]] | image = Yves-Marie André.jpg | image_size = thumb | alt = | caption = | name = Yves-Marie André | other_names = le Père André | birth_date = {{Birth date|1675|05|22}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living philosophers, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead --> | birth_place = [[Châteaulin]], [[Finistère]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1764|02|26|1675|05|22}} <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = [[Caen]], [[Calvados (department)|Calvados]] | school_tradition = | main_interests = [[Aesthetics]] | notable_ideas = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | signature_alt = | quote = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}'''Yves Marie André ''' (1675–1764), also known as '''le Père André''', was a French [[Jesuit]] [[mathematician]], [[philosopher]], and [[essayist]].
André entered the Society of Jesus in 1693. Although distinguished in his scholastic studies, he adhered to [[Gallicanism]] and [[Jansenism]] and was thus considered unsuitable for responsible office by Church authorities. He therefore pursued scientific studies and became royal professor of mathematics at Caen.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Yves Marie André}}</ref>
He is best known for his ''Essai sur le Beau'' (''Essay on Beauty''), a 1741 philosophical work on [[aesthetics]], which made him famous at the time and remained a well-known work into the 19th century.<ref>André, ''Essai sur le Beau'' in ''Œuvres Philosophiques'' (Paris: Adolphe Delahays, 1843).</ref>
